  "opinion": "As a 54-year-old plumber living in Kansas City, I've seen my share of tough conversations, and talking about healthcare and COVID vaccines is no different. With my background, I rely on practical experience over fancy theories. I didn't get much formal education—just primary school—and my parents had vocational or no education, so I value hands-on knowledge. Being a native American and Muslim, I respect traditions and community, but I also trust what works in real life. I'm not one for social media, so I get my info from people I meet on the job or in my hobbies like football and travel. When it comes to COVID vaccines, I think it's about balancing personal choice with common sense. I've had friends and family affected by the virus, and I've seen how vaccines can help prevent serious illness. But I understand folks who are hesitant—maybe they've heard conflicting stories or have their own beliefs. In discussions, I try to listen first, share my own experiences without pushing too hard, and focus on practical outcomes like staying healthy for my family. My low openness score means I'm not quick to change my mind, but my moderate conscientiousness keeps me responsible. I avoid heated arguments because my low agreeableness and extraversion make me prefer calm, one-on-one talks. Ultimately, managing these talks is about respect, patience, and sticking to what you know from life, not just what others say.",
